Based on classical Arabic-language Islamic scholarship, particularly within the fields of Quranic exegesis (tafsir) and scholastic theology (`ilm al-kalām), the concept of tahrif (scriptural corruption) is a cornerstone of the Islamic understanding of previous revelations. It posits that the sacred texts of Judaism (the Tawrat, or Torah) and Christianity (the Injil, or Gospel) have been altered from their original, divinely revealed forms. This doctrine is rooted in Quranic verses and has been extensively debated and categorized by Muslim scholars throughout history, leading to a spectrum of views on the nature and extent of this alleged alteration.
Defining and Categorizing Tahrif
The term tahrif literally means "to distort," "to change," or "to alter." [17, 91] In the context of Islamic theology, it refers to the corruption of the scriptures of the People of the Book (Ahl al-Kitāb), i.e., Jews and Christians. [40] Classical scholars have primarily categorized tahrif into two main types:
Tahrif al-Ma'na (Corruption of the Meaning): This is the distortion of the interpretation, meaning, or application of a text without altering the written words themselves. [16, 19] Early Muslim commentators, including the companion of the Prophet Muhammad, Ibn Abbas, are often cited as holding this view. [17, 82] They argued that no one could alter the actual words of God, but that corruption occurred through misinterpretation and false exegesis. [17, 77] This could involve "twisting their tongues" while reciting the scripture to deceive listeners or deliberately misrepresenting the meaning to conceal certain truths. [18]
Tahrif al-Nass (Corruption of the Text): This is the physical alteration of the scriptural text itself through additions, deletions, or substitutions of words and sentences. [18, 25] This view gained prominence later in Islamic history, most notably with the 11th-century Andalusian scholar Ibn Hazm. [16, 68] Proponents of this view argue that the existing texts of the Torah and Gospels are not the original revelations given to Moses and Jesus. [63]
Some scholars have further broken down the methods of tahrif, including concealing parts of the revelation (kitman), replacing words with others (tabdil), and attributing human writings to God. [39]
Theological Arguments and Textual Evidence
The foundation for the doctrine of tahrif is derived from several verses in the Quran. These verses are interpreted by classical exegetes and theologians as evidence that the People of the Book were not faithful custodians of their scriptures.
Quranic Basis
The primary Quranic verses cited in discussions of tahrif include:
Surah Al-Baqarah 2:75: "Do you then hope that they would believe for you, while a party of them used to hear the word of Allah and then distort it after they had understood it while they were knowing?" This verse is often presented as direct evidence of intentional distortion. [18]
Surah Al-Baqarah 2:79: "So woe to those who write the 'scripture' with their own hands, then say, 'This is from Allah,' in order to exchange it for a small price. Woe to them for what their hands have written and woe to them for what they earn." This verse is seen as a condemnation of forging scripture for worldly gain. [16, 61]
Surah Al-Nisa 4:46: "Among the Jews are those who displace words from their (right) places..." This is taken as a clear indication of altering the text or its meaning. [18]
Surah Al-Ma'idah 5:13: "But because of their breach of their covenant, We cursed them, and made their hearts grow hard. They change the words from their (right) places and have abandoned a good part of the message that was sent to them." This verse connects the act of tahrif with a breach of the covenant with God. [18]
Surah Al-Ma'idah 5:41: "...They distort words from their usages..." This reiterates the accusation of altering the divine message. [25]
Arguments from Ilm al-Kalām (Scholastic Theology)
Theologians, particularly those engaged in polemics, developed rational arguments to substantiate the claims of tahrif. These arguments often revolved around the following points:
Internal Contradictions and Implausibilities: Scholars like Ibn Hazm systematically pointed out what they considered to be chronological and geographical inaccuracies, as well as internal contradictions within the biblical narrative. [16, 64] For example, he highlighted the differing accounts of the calling of the first disciples in the four Gospels as evidence that they could not all be divinely inspired truth. [64]
Theological Impossibilities: Theologians argued that the Bible contains passages that are theologically untenable from an Islamic perspective. This includes anthropomorphic descriptions of God, attributing major sins to prophets, and the doctrine of the Trinity. [16, 67] Such passages, they contended, could not have been part of the original, pure revelation.
Lack of a Reliable Chain of Transmission (Tawatur): A key argument, especially for later scholars like Ibn Hazm, was the perceived lack of a continuous and widespread chain of transmission for the biblical texts that would guarantee their authenticity, in contrast to the Islamic concept of tawatur for the Quran. [16, 62] Ibn Taymiyyah, while taking a more intermediate position, also questioned the reliability of the Gospels' transmission, noting that two of the four Gospels were not authored by eyewitnesses to Jesus's ministry. [35]
The Denial of the Crucifixion: The Quran's statement in Surah An-Nisa 4:157 that Jesus was not killed or crucified but that "it was made to appear to them" is a central point of contention. [73] For many classical scholars, the accounts of the crucifixion in the Gospels are a prime example of textual corruption, as they contradict the Quranic narrative. [63] The theological argument here is that God would not allow His messenger to be defeated and killed in such a humiliating manner. [73, 81]
Specific Examples of Alleged Corruption
Classical Muslim scholars provided numerous specific examples from the Torah and Gospels that they believed were evidence of tahrif al-nass.
In the Torah (Tawrat)
The Posthumous Account of Moses's Death: Ibn Hazm pointed to Deuteronomy 34:5-6, which describes the death and burial of Moses, as clear evidence that Moses could not have written the entirety of the Torah. He argued that this section must have been added by a later author, thus compromising the text's claim to be a direct revelation to Moses. [62]
Ezra as the Author: Ibn Hazm went further to posit that the Torah was largely authored by Ezra ('Uzayr), who, according to some traditions, restored the scriptures after they were lost. [16, 65] This claim sought to sever the direct link between the existing Torah and the revelation to Moses.
Alteration of Prophecies about Muhammad: A common accusation was that Jewish scribes deliberately removed or altered passages that originally prophesied the coming of the Prophet Muhammad. [75] This was often linked to the Quranic claim that they "conceal the truth while they know it."
The Incident of Abraham's Migration: Some traditions allege that the story of Abraham's migration was altered to obscure any connection he had with the Kaaba in Mecca. [75]
In the Gospels (Injil)
Contradictory Genealogies of Jesus: Some scholars pointed to the differences in the genealogies of Jesus presented in the Gospels of Matthew and Luke as a sign of human error and textual corruption.
The Calling of the Disciples: As mentioned, Ibn Hazm analyzed the varying accounts in Matthew 4, Mark 1, Luke 5, and John 1 regarding the calling of the first disciples and concluded that their contradictions prove they are the work of "accursed liars." [64]
The Crucifixion Narrative: The detailed accounts of Jesus's crucifixion are considered a major corruption, as they conflict with the Quranic denial. [63, 73]
The Trinity and the Sonship of God: Passages that are used to support the doctrine of the Trinity and the divine sonship of Jesus, such as the use of "Son of God," were seen as later additions or misinterpretations of terms that could also mean "servant." [75] Ibn Hazm argued that the doctrine of the Trinity was a later invention by church elders without a solid scriptural basis. [67]
Luke's Prologue: Ibn Hazm interpreted the prologue of the Gospel of Luke, where the author states his intention to write an orderly account, as an admission that the work is a human composition and not a divine revelation. [80]
