It is crucial to note that there was not a monolithic view on tahrif in classical Islam. Early scholars like al-Tabari (d. 923) tended to favor tahrif al-ma'na, suggesting that the texts were largely intact but misinterpreted. [18, 82] Fakhr al-Din al-Razi (d. 1209), a prominent theologian and exegete, discussed both possibilities but seemed to lean towards corruption of meaning, arguing that widespread textual alteration would have been difficult once a scripture became well-known. [21, 39]
