The Definition and Categories of Tahrif
Linguistically, tahrif derives from the Arabic root ḥ-r-f, which means to change, alter, or distort. In theological terms, it refers to the alteration of God's revealed scriptures. Classical Muslim scholars have broadly categorized tahrif into two main types:
Tahrif al-Ma'na (Corruption of the Meaning): This refers to the distortion of the interpretation of a text without altering the text itself. This can include misinterpreting words, taking verses out of context, or concealing their true meaning. Early Muslim scholars, in their engagement with the People of the Book (Jews and Christians), often focused on this form of corruption.
Tahrif al-Lafz or Tahrif al-Nass (Corruption of the Text): This is the more severe allegation of the physical alteration of the scriptural text itself, which can involve the addition, omission, or substitution of words or passages. While early commentators were often more focused on interpretive distortion, later scholars, most notably Ibn Hazm of Cordoba, championed the argument for widespread textual corruption.
