Analysis: The Sabbatean-Frankist institutional trail reveals two distinct but parallel models of "infiltrative assimilation." The Dönmeh leveraged economic dominance within a cosmopolitan urban center to achieve political influence, gradually entering state institutions from a position of financial power. The Frankists, by contrast, executed a direct socio-political maneuver—a mass, sponsored conversion—to bypass traditional social barriers and enter the landed aristocracy (szlachta) in a single generation. Both groups used a dual identity, strict endogamy, and clandestine religious practices as core mechanisms to preserve their communities while outwardly conforming. This finding adds a crucial framework for understanding how crypto-religious groups can successfully integrate into and influence powerful host institutions, not by abandoning their identity, but by weaponizing their assimilation.
